1 - Install Touchégg dependences:
    $ sudo apt-get install build-essential libqt4-dev utouch libx11-6

2 - Compile and install Touchégg:
    $ qmake
    $ make
    $ sudo make install

3 - Go to your /usr/share/X11/xorg.conf.d/ path and check if exits any file like
    "nn-<trackpad name>.conf".
    If exits change the Driver "<driver name>" line to Driver "evdev".
    For example, this is my 60-magictrackpad.conf file:

    Section "InputClass"
         Identifier "Magic Trackpad"
         MatchUSBID "05ac:030e"
         Driver "evdev"
    EndSection

4 - If  not  exits  you need  edit your  /etc/X11/xorg.conf  file and  add  this
    content, obiusly change the Identifier. Check this:
    https://code.google.com/p/touchegg/wiki/ConfigurationDevices

5 - If /etc/X11/xorg.conf file don't exits create it:
    Press CTRL+ALT+F1 (Important! press CTRL+ALT+F7 to return to the X mode) and
    login.
    Run "sudo service gdm stop" for Gnome or "sudo service kdm stop" for KDE.
    Run "sudo Xorg -configure" and "sudo mv xorg.conf.new /etc/X11/xorg.conf".
    Reestart X with "sudo service gdm start" or "sudo service kdm start"
    Edit the /etc/X11/xorg.conf like in step 4.

6 - Run Touchégg:
    $ touchegg

7 - Make a gesture, for example drag two fingers over your trackpad. If all
    works fine, the name of the gesture will appear.

8 - To use your own configuration:
    $ mkdir $HOME/.touchegg
    $ cp /usr/share/touchegg/touchegg.conf $HOME/.touchegg/touchegg.conf

    And edit it... GUI in progress ;)



--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Activar efectos KWin con RUN_COMMAND:

Para ver los distintos efectos:

 $ qdbus org.kde.kglobalaccel /component/kwin shortcutNames

Pudiendose activar, por ejemplo, el expose:

 $ qdbus org.kde.kglobalaccel /component/kwin invokeShortcut Expose
